  { q: 'How do I convert a string to JSON?', a: 'In JavaScript, use JSON.parse(yourString) to convert a JSON string to a JavaScript object. To do it online, paste the string into TextWonder\'s JSON Formatter — it parses the string and shows the formatted JSON object.' },
  { q: 'What is a JSON string vs a JSON object?', a: 'A JSON string is text that looks like JSON but is stored as a string variable (e.g. \'{"name":"Alice"}\'). A JSON object is the parsed JavaScript value you can work with. JSON.parse() converts the string to the object.' },
  { q: 'How do I convert a JavaScript object to JSON?', a: 'Use JSON.stringify(yourObject) in JavaScript. This converts a JavaScript object to a JSON string. For example, JSON.stringify({name:"Alice",age:30}) returns \'{"name":"Alice","age":30}\'.' },
  { q: 'Why does JSON.parse() throw an error?', a: 'Common reasons: the string is not valid JSON (missing quotes around keys, trailing commas, single quotes instead of double quotes), or the string contains escaped characters that need unescaping first. Use TextWonder\'s JSON Formatter to spot the syntax error.' },
  { q: 'How do I convert an object to JSON string in Python?', a: 'Use import json and json.dumps(your_dict) to convert a Python dict to a JSON string. Use json.loads(your_string) to parse a JSON string back to a dict.' },
];
