<h2>Method 2: JSON.parse() in JavaScript</h2>

<p>
  In JavaScript, convert a JSON string to an object with:
</p>

<pre><code>const jsonString = '&#123;"name":"Alice","age":30&#125;';
const obj = JSON.parse(jsonString);
console.log(obj.name); // "Alice"</code></pre>

<p>
  Always wrap <code>JSON.parse()</code> in a try/catch to handle invalid strings:
</p>

<pre><code>try &#123;
  const obj = JSON.parse(jsonString);
  // use obj here
&#125; catch (e) &#123;
  console.error('Invalid JSON:', e.message);
&#125;</code></pre>

<h2>Method 3: Object to JSON String (JSON.stringify)</h2>

<p>
  To convert a JavaScript object <em>to</em> a JSON string:
</p>

<pre><code>const obj = &#123; name: "Alice", age: 30 &#125;;
const jsonString = JSON.stringify(obj, null, 2);
// Result: '&#123;\n  "name": "Alice",\n  "age": 30\n&#125;'</code></pre>

<p>
  <code>null, 2</code> adds 2-space indentation. Use <code>null, 0</code> (or just <code>JSON.stringify(obj)</code>) for compact/minified output.
</p>

<h2>Method 4: Python — json.loads() and json.dumps()</h2>

<p>In Python:</p>

<pre><code>import json

# String → Python dict (equivalent to JSON object)
data = json.loads('&#123;"name": "Alice", "age": 30&#125;')
print(data["name"])  # Alice

# Python dict → JSON string
json_string = json.dumps(data, indent=2)
print(json_string)</code></pre>

<h2>Why Is My JSON String Invalid?</h2>

<p>Common reasons <code>JSON.parse()</code> fails:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Single quotes:</strong> JSON requires double quotes — <code>'name'</code> is invalid, <code>"name"</code> is correct.</li>
  <li><strong>Trailing commas:</strong> <code>[1, 2, 3,]</code> is invalid JSON (trailing comma after last item).</li>
  <li><strong>Unquoted keys:</strong> <code>&#123;name: "Alice"&#125;</code> is invalid — keys must be quoted: <code>&#123;"name": "Alice"&#125;</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Double-escaped backslashes:</strong> Strings received from APIs may be double-encoded. Use the <a href="/devwonder/json-formatter">JSON Formatter</a> to spot the issue.</li>
</ul>

